results.name: Largest primitive prime factor of Fibonacci number F(n), or 1 if no primitive.
comment: Carmichael proved that a(n) > 1 if n > 12.
See A001578 (smallest primitive prime factor of F(n)) and A061446 (primitive part of F(n)) for more links.
link: R. D. Carmichael, On the numerical factors of the arithmetic forms α^n±β^n, Annals of Math., 15 (1913), 30-70.
Ron Knott, Fibonacci numbers and special prime factors
example: The prime factors of F(46)= 139 * 461 * 28657 that do not divide any smaller Fibonacci number are 139 and 461, so a(46) = 461.
mathematica: prms={}; Table[f=First/@FactorInteger[Fibonacci[n]]; p=Complement[f, prms]; prms=Join[prms, p]; If[p=={}, 1, Last[p]], {n, 50}]
program: (Perl) use ntheory ":all"; my %s; for (1..100) { my @f = factor(lucasu(1,-1,$_)); pop @f while @f && $s{$f[-1]}++; say "$_ ", $f[-1] || 1; }  # _Dana Jacobsen_, Oct 13 2015
